# Migrating `TimedExecutor` to .NET 8

## Key Problem

`Thread.Abort()` and `Thread.ResetAbort()` throw `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 8. The cooperative cancellation pattern via `CancellationToken` is the replacement.

## Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        var task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Will throw if the task doesn't complete in time
            task.Wait(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException($"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }

        // Unwrap AggregateException for single faults
        if (task.IsFaulted)
            throw task.Exception!.InnerExceptions.Count == 1
                ? task.Exception.InnerException!
                : task.Exception;

        return task.Result;
    }

    // Async overload (preferred in modern code)
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<CancellationToken, Task<T>> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            return await work(cts.Token).WaitAsync(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException($"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

## Usage

```csharp
var executor = new TimedExecutor();

// The work function must observe the token
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(ct =>
{
    while (!ct.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        // do incremental work...
    }
    ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
    return value;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
```

## Critical Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---------|--------|
| **Non-cooperative work** | Unlike `Thread.Abort()`, cancellation tokens can't force-kill code that ignores them. Long-running library calls (e.g., blocking I/O) must accept a `CancellationToken` or they won't stop. |
| **`Thread.ResetAbort()` removal** | No equivalent exists — remove entirely. |
| **Fire-and-forget leaks** | If work ignores the token, the `Task` keeps running after timeout. For truly uncooperative code, isolate it in a separate **process** instead. |
| **`default(T)` with NRT** | In .NET 8 with nullable reference types enabled, `default` for reference types is `null` — use `T?` or `default!` to avoid warnings. |
| **Exception semantics change** | `Task.Wait()` wraps in `AggregateException`; `await` unwraps automatically. Choose based on caller expectations. |

## Escape Hatch for Uncooperative Code

If you absolutely cannot modify the work delegate (e.g., third-party library):

```csharp
// Last resort — background thread that gets abandoned (leaked) on timeout
public T ExecuteWithTimeoutUncooperative<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    T result = default!;
    Exception? error = null;

    var thread = new Thread(() =>
    {
        try { result = work(); }
        catch (Exception ex) { error = ex; }
    }) { IsBackground = true }; // won't block process exit

    thread.Start();

    if (!thread.Join(timeout))
        throw new TimeoutException($"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");

    if (error != null)
        throw new AggregateException(error);

    return result;
}
```

> ⚠️ This **leaks the thread** on timeout — it keeps running until the process exits. Only acceptable when process-level isolation isn't feasible.

## Summary

Replace `Thread.Abort()` → cooperative `CancellationToken`. The delegate signature must change (`Func<T>` → `Func<CancellationToken, T>`) — this is an intentional breaking change that makes timeout behavior explicit and safe.
